The Government wants to limit the torture of the "witches," as published in a brochure
Women considered as witches in Burkina Faso share certain characteristics.
They are often old, unable to work, for example, for health reasons, are single and have no children.
Women who "turn" witches are sent to an isolated area, so that they do not harm the rest of the town.
"Men rarely suffer such as that."
"Healthy young women are not isolated either, because they help work and have children," explains a nun who, in the state capital of West Africa, Burkina Faso is working in a special residence of more than 100 women expelled from their communities.
The local government has decided to oppose this unusual "social measure."
He issued an information brochure that should help prevent witch hunting.
However, this has a hit.
"More than 70% of adults in Burkina Faso can't read," says the Die Standard newspaper about the disadvantages of written awareness.
Allegations of witchcraft are also common in other African countries.
In Gana, a neighbouring country of Burkina Faso, last week Ammy Hemmah, 72, died when three women and two men tortured her, covered her with gasoline and burned her.
The news appeared on the BBC.
The authors claim that it was due to an unfortunate group of circumstances.
According to his version, the woman was lit in the oil that is used for ritual anointions.
He was on fire when the group wanted to "expel the evil spirits" from the woman.
The isolation of "witches" is supported by people of all levels of education.
The newspaper Der Standard quoted a 42-year-old businessman from Burkina Faso: "Human soul devorers always represented a danger," he said.
While in Burkina Faso the Government is trying to appease the witch hunt, in the Gambia last year the President still took part in it.
"Gambian President Jammeh, after his aunt's death, launched a wide hunt for witches who had allegedly been related to his death and had tried to kill the president himself by means of black magic."
"To help him, he brought Chamans from nearby Guinea who, protected by police, military and the President's personal escort, were forced to take men and women randomly chosen among the Gambian peoples to the President's property in Kanilai," said Amnesty International in his report.
On the farm, the arrested people had to drink a podium of herbs with hallucinogenic effects that also caused them intestinal and kidney problems.
Two of those arrested did not survive the stay on the estate.
After international pressure, some 1,000 people were finally released.
The tenant of Bakala: is heated with coal stoves and signs a higher rent
The man, old and old, crossed the doors of the customer service center of the RPG Byty company of the "coal magnate" Zdeńek Bakala, the largest private owner of apartments for rent in the Czech Republic.
Under his arm he had documents with the new three-story rental contracts: his, his daughter's, and his son's, who is serving his sentence.
All three have just been caught up in the liberalization of rents.
Instead of CZK 3,500 per month, the child will pay as of next year CZK 4,100 for a two-room apartment with separate second-category kitchen.
"In addition, it does not have hot water and the heating is based on a solid fuel boiler," the man shows with his finger in his son's new contract, on whose signature he has full powers.
"But I signed it," he explains half-angry, half-resigned.
The civil association BytyOKD.cz, which described the new rental conditions as "incorrect and indecent," recommends that tenants not sign the new contracts and wait until 7 December, when it will publish a guide informing about how to proceed in these cases.
But, in the face of this, the man only makes an admonition.
"Each one says one thing," he says with a bad face.
Ostrava is becoming a great test laboratory for liberalization.
After New Year will happen with the vast majority of the floors that, in the Czech Republic, were so far under a regulated rent.
Therefore, Aktuálně.cz decided to visit the "laboratory" in person.
The RPG mining waiting room is one of the four in Ostrava and, on Tuesday at 9: 00, it was already full.
Right next to the doors are the security guards and next to them a machine to take number.
"Rental 2011," can be read on a bright button of your touch screen.
When you push it, a little piece of paper with a number comes out of the machine.
It hardly gives time to read "157" and the number already appears on the large screen located on the top of the room.
In a second, you're in line.
Soon after, an old marriage comes to ask, but the crowd in the room is not here for the new rentals.
Most people come to solve common problems, as in the past: requests for arrangements, insurance issues and similar matters.
The letters with the new rental contracts will reach in Ostrava to the mailboxes of the tenants of most of the 44,000 floors belonging to RPG around mid-November.
RPG Byty offers them a rent increase of between 15 and 38% in the cards.
On November 18, a special window opens at the customer service center for new rentals.
"It's been working for a week, so it's starting," they answer, after briefly hesitating, the workers who are in it when the client shows up as a journalist.
Liberalization and the old floors for Bakala miners are the most sensitive issues in the area.
Before the elections, the Vice-President of Parliament, from Ostrava, Lubomír Zaorálek, from the ČSSD, has already dealt with them in high and clear terms and now they appear in the newspapers of the area.
"Twenty years later I want a new floor."
"They didn't even change my fucking bathroom dish," the man mentioned in the introduction is unchoked.
According to the workers, at the moment they come more than anything retired to check if they receive a rent discount if they sign on time, as the RPG special offer promises.
The remaining tenants who sign the new contract by 15 December will also receive half of the February rent discount.
However, the window of mining "liberalization" is certainly not able to dispel the avalanche of doubt.
"Of the 360 customers who were here yesterday, only asked about the rent in 2011 about forty or fifty people," the window employee estimates.
Meanwhile, RPG proposes on the web and on its boards to hold individual meetings on contracts where necessary.
If the two parties fail to reach an agreement on rent, an independent judge shall settle the matter.
"It is not a threat, but information about the only way to proceed possible and fully in accordance with the law," RPG warns on its pages.
"No one will be judged here," says one of RPG Byty's employees and a man who is on the street in front of the customer service center gives him, at least in part, the reason.
"I receive a pension of 13,000 and I have 5,000 left for food; I have no means to go to court," he says.
But, immediately, the employee sows the doubt.
"We'll see."
"Mr. Zaorálek tells them in the media not to sign, so maybe people will wait," he says.
The regulation of rent will cease to exist in most of the Czech Republic at the beginning of 2011 and, according to RPG Byty, its increase is an economic necessity.
"The current rents still do not cover even the amounts necessary for the maintenance of the community fund," says Pavel Klimeš, director of the residential portfolio of RPG Byty, who adds that the careless state of the community that angers the tenants is, for the owners, the main reason for increasing the rent.
While during the five years that passed between 2005 and 2010 RPG was able to invest in apartments four billion, in the four years that will go from 2011 to 2014 the figure will increase to 5.2 billion.
The large screen that hangs from the ceiling, in front of the waiting room seats, now repeats some data that highlight in red.
"The increase in rent in 2011 by 15% and less applies to 31,200 apartments, that is, more than 90% of RPG properties."
"In addition, it will always be at most CZK 7.50 per square metre per month," is indicated on the screen.
Just increase by 38% the rental of 400 floors of the RPG portfolio.
"In such cases, this is an increase from extremely low amounts of 19.66 kroner per square metre," says RPG.
On 2,600 floors, the rent will remain unchanged next year.
RPG Byty promises that liberalization will not suddenly affect rents, but will scale from four to eight years.
In addition, he adds the following commitment: the company will invest all the money from the increase of the rent (see the graph) again on the floors, mainly in savings in heating: new windows and heating.
Priority shall be given to persons who sign the rental raise agreement.
Architects have understood that offices also need day care
The Avriopint administrative building in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch.Design.
No one would say that he also hides in his interior a small nursery with all the same to such facilities: colored walls, creative furniture and even a miniature park on the outside terrace.
Since October last year, the children of the employees of Arch.Design. can come to it.
The Arch.Design architectural project company, from which many known buildings from Brno came out, thought from the first sketches of the Avriopint building to include a space for its mini-business.
In the company work about 90 people, mainly at the age of the baby boom and wanted to allow the architects and artists to return to work soon after maternity.
Along with the possibility of a reduced schedule, day care is one of the benefits that Arch.Design offers to its workers within the framework of its social program.
The builders and architects thus have the possibility to combine a demanding profession with the care of the children.
The mini-business was an idea of Arch.Designu's own employees and, with the support of the management, they managed to obtain funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company's mini-business is financed through the European Social Fund under the Operational Programme for Human Resources and Employment, as well as the State budget of the Czech Republic.
With the funding granted (over CZK 2.8 million), they were able to purchase the equipment and, after two years, to hire qualified staff and services.
When the funding is exhausted (two years), the company Arch.Design has an obligation to keep the mini-business running with its own funds for three years.
The preparation of the project lasted one year and the Economy Rating company contributed to the application for funding.
The care of children is provided by qualified personnel; in addition, a nurse and a teacher from the Ministry of Education are present all day long for their care. The day-care centre currently accommodates children without age limits, although most of them are under the age of three.
Since it is a "mini-shop," it can only accommodate a maximum of five children simultaneously, although with the shifts they come more during the day.
The operation of the day-care centre is flexible to adapt to the needs of the parents and the children of all workers have the same right to use the day-care centre, regardless of the hierarchy within the company.
Although this is individual education and care, the contents of the mini-school programme are comparable to the regular pre-school programme.
In it children not only play, but also receive quality education: from basic learning to school preparation, they teach even English.
The class not only has toys and board games, but also a computer for children.
The presence of young children in the company itself creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can go to see their children at any time and avoid the stress of late picking up children from school when they are away from their workplace.
Thus, parents are more productive while working.
It is not surprising that this naturally generates a relationship of loyalty between the worker and his employer.
In this way, Arch.Design is among the companies that they sign that they offer a great advantage for the admission of new workers: they support the family and, ultimately, this programme strengthened the marketing of personnel.
The house of the bones continues to fascinate after 100 years. Watch the interiors of Gaudí
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs remember the column of a dinosaur and the balconies look like the mouth of an open fish.
This is the Casa Batlló, in Barcelona, of the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Because of its similar shape to a skeleton, the locals nicknamed it "the house of the bones."
Its organic forms, its striking colors, the new use of stone, the fragments of tiles and mosaics, a facade that reminds of the scales and the omnipresent lines gently curved, all this is typical of the secession of Antoni Gaudí.
The cover of the house plays with oniric lines, delicate colors and textures drawn from nature and fauna.
With more attention, a certain geometry, rhythm and a carefully thought-out order are observed.
At night, the whole facade of the house seems even more impressive, as it is illuminated in such a way that the brightness of the colors is improved.
Serpentea and the torsion of forms continues to surprise us also inside.
The wavy wood copies the frames of the windows, the rails, the ornaments of the doors, the pears and the signs.
The Casa Batlló, which is located in the Eixample district at number 43 of the lively shopping street of Passeig de Grácia, emerged from the remodeling of a house in 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
The reconstruction lasted two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the rich industrial Josep Batlló, initially insisted on bringing down the previous building and starting from scratch, but soon accepted Gaudí's idea of a new and cheaper reconstruction.
However, the Casa Batlló, made up of various apartments, was not designed by Antoni Gaudí alone.
The architect Josep María Jujol collaborated in the design.
In fact, in its plans of the project, ornaments emerged for the representative apartment of the owner of the property and the mosaics used on the facade.
On the facade also workers other creators and artists.
The collaboration in the proposals of the Casa Batlló was the beginning of Jujol's successful collaboration with Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of the Casa Milá and Güell de Gaudí Park, where other pieces of the house are located.
Because of its organic form, the premises soon after its completion were nicknamed "the house of the bones."
Others, due to the specific mechanism of opening the windows, began to call it "the house of the yawns."
It is also said that, on top of the construction, the sword of St. George, patron of Catalonia, appears.
Other sculptural elements of the construction hide religious motives.
Gaudí designed a unique system in the house for the central heating period with ventilation vents and the typical chimneys.
It may be strange to see his inclination of forty-five degrees.
During the construction, Gaudí did not at all respect the construction rules of the moment and was not allowed to influence them.
Even so, the construction obtained the corresponding permission from the beginning, although clearly in it the data indicated on the planned reconstruction were so vague that, two years later, at its completion, the town hall was so shocked with the result that it asked to be corrected.
He was concerned, for example, that the construction included columns even to the public sidewalk.
The arrangements were never made, but on the contrary: only fifteen days after the city's request, Josep Batlló requested (and obtained) permission to rent the two highest floors of the building.
On the lower floors the owner himself was installed.
In the gallery on the second floor was the living room and on the third floor the bedrooms and the private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The six-story house is completely crossed by a staircase that leads to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the reform were to break all the straight angles and lines, covering them with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of space connection.
The common part can be fully connected by opening the doors of the rooms and a larger group can communicate in this way without any problems, without giving up the privacy necessary for more intimate conversations.
The house, with the reconstruction of Gaudí, not only obtained a new facade, but also an unusual roof and two additional floors.
It is also impressive how Gaudí plays with light, white and blue tiles that cover the inner courtyard and skylights.
The game with the two colors provides the maximum light on all the floors of the house.
It was simply based on the principle that white reflects more light than dark colors, which on the contrary absorb the rays of sun.
Anyone can visit the Casa Batlló, which in 2005 was added to the World Heritage List of the Humanity of Unesco.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and recharged apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to open the doors to the public in 2002, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
With the visits they confirmed, or discovered, that this is a very beneficial business and extended the visits to the common area and to the attic, including the roof terrace.
The price of the entrance to the monument is not negligible, it reaches 16.50 euros, although students, retirees and the holders of the tourist cards get a 20% discount.
The amount significantly exceeds the price of the entry of other Gaudí buildings in the city.
