More and more parents use people's monitoring devices to control their children
The fear for children leads more and more people to think about controlling them by GPS.
The system, initially designed for vehicle tracking, can also follow the movement of people and thus contribute, for example, in case of the disappearance of the nine-year-old girl Anička Janatková.
At the moment the device has the approximate size of a match box, but it will soon be reduced to the size of a watch.
Many people were afraid of the case of the missing Anička and information was started on the means available to better protect their children.
Even at the cost of invading your privacy.
"We all try to tell us that it is not a question of spying, but of another means of reducing the chances of a tragedy," says Petr Pilin of the company Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of monitoring devices in the Czech market.
"I recognize that, in certain cases, such devices can be abused, for example if they are put in someone's bag without their knowledge, but we have not yet encountered such cases."
"Most customers really buy it for security reasons," Pilin adds.
In their view, children should always know what the "box" is for and how it is used in the event of an emergency.
The child psychologist Dana Bočková warns about the fact that, if the child does not want to take him, he will simply throw him away.
"Even the younger children show great creativity when it comes to intentionally losing certain things if they want to prevent them from being controlled."
"Before, parents were very confident in mobile phones, but they could be turned off as easily as the tracking device," says Bočková.
In his view, it is questionable whether such a device is really useful in the event of an attack.
"If it is a prepared kidnapping, the author will almost always check whether the child has any electronic device that can reveal his / her location."
"Now it's the phone."
"As the use of the tracking devices is being extended, it will also look for them, since their sale will no doubt be made with a lot of publicity."
"In such cases, criminals are always one step ahead of the police," says the psychologist.
However, it adds that such devices can help in the case of an improvised attack of a paedophile.
According to Robert Čech of the company RC Monitoring, which provides tracking services for both vehicles and people, even if, after an attack, the monitoring device is immediately destroyed, its presence can help.
"The device can be configured to send the position regularly after a certain period."
"If you suffer damage, at least you will facilitate the last position of the person in question."
"The most expensive devices have an integrated tilt meter, so if the person simply slips and stays still, the device will immediately issue a warning with the position in question," says Čech.
In his view, such a service can be obtained even with mobile phones with navigation, where only special software should be installed.
The problem with current tracking units is that at the moment these are devices with a size similar to a match box or smaller mobile phones.
They can therefore be lost.
According to Pilin de Macro Weil, this is why tests are currently being carried out with devices that look like a digital watch.
"In addition, they will have the added advantage that a possible aggressor may not identify the device."
"Or to identify him after some time, which can make the police earn time," he adds.
Even if the tracking devices are carried on the wrist or hanging, they will continue to use the same technology used for vehicle tracking.
This is the position check with a GPS system (used in the usual navigation in the car) combined with the function of a mobile phone that communicates the current position.
