So far I'm still living from the contacts I got thanks to the contest.
The winning of the "Entrepreneur of the Year" contest helped Lukáš Pytloun to sell the franchises of his hotel.
The last edition, won the "Entrepreneur of the Year" contest, the 28-year-old entrepreneur Lukáš Pytloun of Liberec.
Her success story seems to be taken out of a movie.
Lukáš Pytloun loved to travel.
He realized abroad that there was a need for quality accommodation at a good price in Liberec.
With the savings he brought together with seasonal work abroad and a bank credit he bought a house that was half-run, composed of five floors.
Considering that he was still studying his third year in college, he was really brave.
"At present, the quality-price ratio of the accommodation in our area prompted me to do something about it," says Lukáš Pytloun.
He started renting the first floor rebuilt to foreign workers.
All the income I got was investing them back in the building, which gradually turned into a 54-room pension.
Since then, in seven years in the business, it has gradually managed to open in Liberec four pensions, two style restaurants and two hotels with a total capacity of about 300 in all categories of accommodation.
The most comfortable of all was, until recently, the four-star Pytloun design hotel.
This year, however, it opened another of the same quality.
"We just signed a contract with a hotel in Ostrov u Tisé, to which we have sold our franchise concept, and other people are showing interest in a Pytloun franchise," said the number one businessman last year.
"This sale of hotel opening licences helped to a great extent to win the 'Entrepreneur of the Year' contest," he added.
The victory increased its fame and popularity both in and around Liberec.
"People recognized me on the street, they still congratulated me often and, I must say, it was very nice," he recalls.
It certainly recommends that everyone want to try some company to participate in the competition.
But he believes that there is no need to win, but that participation is already beneficial.
He claims that, so far, he continues to live from the contacts and acquaintances that, without the contest, he may not have obtained.
"With some people I met thanks to the contest I have started to collaborate regularly."
The fame associated with success, in his opinion, also included in the employees,
in total about seventy.
"I have seen that they show greater loyalty and are proud to participate in something that received general recognition."
"It is not, much less, my own personal success, but it is the result of the hard work of the entire team."
"It is only my name that appears on the front page," Lukáš Pytloun says modestly today.
I wish my successor a year quieter than we've had in Farmet.
The euphoria for victory soon dissipated by the impact of the crisis.
Thanks to the hard work of the winner, it is possible that Farmet has already been through the worst.
The owner of the company Farmet, Karel Žárský, received the first prize in the last edition of the Vodafone contest "Company of the Year," last year at the "Slavic House" in Prague.
The jury valued his efforts, with which he managed to turn a small technical workshop in Česká Skaliza into a firm with a turnover of hundreds of millions.
"I can say that the prize not only encouraged me, but all my collaborators and improved our confidence in fighting competition," says last year's winner.
The history of the Farmet company begins with the desire to do something useful.
Therefore, when the State proposed to Karel Žárský's father the rental of a small workshop as compensation for the property embargo during communism, he did not hesitate too much; he resigned his position in the company in which he worked and, with a couple of colleagues, founded the company with his father of plastic batteries.
Soon after, they began to specialize in vegetable oil presses.
Eight years later they became the largest manufacturer of automatic presses in central Europe.
They also had a greater presence among the non-specialized public after achieving success in the competition in the media.
"Not only did our customers start to consider the Farmet brand to be considerably better, but also foreign partners began to value collaboration with a company that was more successful in their country," says Karel Žárský.
