A survey that reveals ridiculous standards
The Absurdez of the year survey is part of the corporate tournament for the fourth time.
It has already managed to eliminate some ridiculous rules.
The unknown winner of the new edition of the Absurdez survey of the year was the obligation to bring to the administration documents that officials can access online.
The decision was taken by more than one third of the nearly four thousand voters.
For example, the social security administration requested an extract from the commercial register, although its officials can obtain it with two mouse movements.
Thanks to the survey, this has changed.
"The Czech social security administration will no longer ask for an extract from the commercial register when it checks the insured's taxes," said ČSSZ's spokesman Jana Buraňová.
The aim of the Absurdez of the year survey is to consult the rules and regulations that companies and employers in Czech Republic must respect and to try to eliminate those that are absurd.
This year it is part of the business tournament of the publication Hospodářské noviny for the fourth time and begins to create a hobby also among the general public.
While last year's edition had the participation of three thousand voters, this year it reached almost four thousand.
And it is not surprising, since we still have a number of full legal obligations that must be respected simply to trade.
"Perhaps in the number of roles necessary for the tax declaration we are in the world's first place," says Karel Havlíček of the Association of Small and Medium-sized Enterprises and Entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic.
For years now, the simplification of business standards has been a stated goal of all governments.
However, compared to the rest of the world, the situation of improvement particularly in the Czech Republic.
According to the World Bank, from the point of view of the conditions for a company, the Czech Republic is in position 74th, that is, eight posts worse than last year.
The Absurdez of the Year competition was held for the first time in 2006 and each year is repeated in the same way.
Anyone can indicate some administrative or bureaucratic absurdity every year between April and the end of September, when the competition is closed.
The proposals can be made on the website www.firrooku.cz. Then the competition organizer selects seven candidates for the "anti-prize" and, during October, allows the public to vote on the Internet through www.firrooku.cz / absurdito and www.ihned.cz.
He wins the absurdity that receives the most votes.
This year's survey presented more than a hundred, in particular 105 rules and regulations that make no sense.
The examples were sent by both entrepreneurs and professional and journalist associations.
Among the "finalists" of the competition was, for example, the requirement that vehicles for the maintenance of roads and motorways pay the toll or that employers with twenty employees, two offices and two bathrooms paint the walls every two years.
The list of this year's 70 proposals is published on the pages of the competition.
The announcement of the contest, which is always held in early November in the square of Wenceslao in Prague, is part of an event in which people from the political and social world often participate.
This year, for example, they attended this event of the Eva Svobodová competition, director of the Association of Small and Medium-sized Enterprises and Employers of the Czech Republic, or Petr Kužel, President of the Chamber of Commerce of the Republic.
"Economic prosperity cannot be sustained if the State continually hampers entrepreneurs, so my goal is to eliminate at least 30 paragraphs each year that are currently unnecessarily complicating trade," said Martin Kocurek, Minister of Industry and Trade.
Efforts to eliminate absurd regulations do not remain in the water of drafts.
In 2007, what most disturbed people was the employer's obligation to communicate with a three-day advance to the business office in the area of permanent operation, the intention to go to a fair or exhibition with a position.
This obligation was eliminated in the new industrial law.
The obligation that ended in second place in the number of votes in 2007, that is, the communication to the work office by their foreign workers of work trips of up to 30 days, was removed in the law of the so-called green card.
And the third one's the winner.
The Absurdez of 2009 was the regulation for physiotherapists to have in their consultation a large mirror, a refrigerator and two floor scales.
This year, therefore, the Ministry of Health issued a communication saying that it had removed the obligation to have a refrigerator.
