Families are required to pay an additional fee of several hundred kroner per month
Since January, households will have to pay not only for all types of energy, but also for water and electricity, heating supplements and, in some cases, higher rents.
As a result, families will have to remove several hundred kroner a month more than now from the portfolio from January.
The price of electricity increases by 4.6%, the gas by about 2%, in some cities will have to pay up to 10% more for the water supply and many also increase the price of central heating.
The increase in electricity for families living in apartments should be about 100 kroner a year more than now.
However, the main electricity providers reduced prices, as support for energy production from renewable sources, in particular photovoltaics, has increased.
However, gas is moderately increased, especially at the time when heating is used most and, therefore, consumption is higher.
In this case, they must also have a couple more hundred kroner per year.
While electricity and gas are growing all over the country, the price change for central heating varies from place to place.
The price increase is mainly planned by the largest municipality.
For example, the households of Pardubice or Hradec Králové will pay from January for central heating about 50 kroner per month, while the families of Liberec will pay more than 1,000 kroner per year.
Residents in Prague will also have to bear a 9% increase in the price of water and heating, especially if the city increases the rental of infrastructure.
If the rent does not vary, the Prussians will pay an additional 6.8%.
The prices in Prague, however, will remain among the lowest in the country.
In the north of Bohemia, where current prices are among the highest, both rates will be increased by 7.4%.
They can significantly increase the rental prices of 450,000 rented apartments in Prague, where the regulation will end in January.
For example, the company CPI Byty, which owns in Ústí nad Labem about 2,500 floors, will increase the rent from January by up to 100%.
The company will bring to the courts those who do not agree with the new rent.
The regulated rents, which benefit residents of about 300,000 floors, could increase next year to 10%.
The Czech young people get drunk with Fernet and rum. The beer is no longer in shape, because it takes effect slowly.
Fernet, rum, vodka and even good whiskeys stolen from their parents.
These are the drinks that cause young drinkers to end up in medical care at a age of less than 15 years.
Children who end up lying in the hospital continuously to overcome the hangover are no longer an exception.
This is derived from the experience of doctors who encounter such cases in the hospital's pediatric admissions.
"Drinking beer or wine is no longer in fashion, because it takes them a long time to get drunk."
"Now the fashion is the strong alcoholic drinks," the head of pediatrics at the Hořovice Hospital in central Bohemia, Luděk Pelikán, tells Právo.
"When you get a bottle from your father's cupboard, it can be whiskey, but it's usually Fernet and vodka."
"The vodka has the advantage that it is lightened with juice and that it does not smell so much," he explains.
This is also confirmed by the spokesman for Motol University Hospital, Eva Jurinová.
"It's usually Fernet or rum."
"These are modern alcoholic beverages, particularly among schoolchildren."
"In some cases, they use spirits they took at home," adds Jurinová.
According to Chief Pelikan, 13-14-year-old drinkers are the ones who usually appear in hospitals.
Before Hořovice, where he has worked since this year, he worked for a decade in pediatrics in Motol, where ambulances took young people from nearby areas.
"A girl had to come in maybe four times."
"It started at the age of 12, when they brought it with 3.5 alcohol in blood, in addition to a mixture with ecstasy," the department's doctor says about this case.
"He was at the Holešovice fair at some dance party."
"The interesting thing is that your mother was not surprised that your daughter was missing 48 hours," the boss is surprised.
It is precisely the parents' lack of interest or even their clear tolerance for drinking by their children that is considered the main cause of the increase in alcohol consumption among young people.
Experts point out that in the case of children, there is no proper talk of dependence.
"An alcoholic means a person who has had a chronic dependence on alcohol for several years, with all the phenomena associated with it, which does not occur in children."
"In those who drink alcohol repeatedly, it is due rather to a systematically failed social or family environment," explains Chief Pelikán.
According to the spokesman Jurinová, forty drunk children were hospitalized this year at Motol's paediatric clinic until mid-November.
However, statistics only show those who come with serious poisoning and must remain in the hospital.
Young drinkers who, after a medical examination, go home to the parents or the police, do not count.
In addition to cases where children simply meet after school and drink spirits, for Pelikan there are three seasonal ups and downs that can be mentioned: the witch's day, the end of the year and the end of the school year.
"In such circumstances, drink by the bad notes or, on the contrary, celebrate the beginning of the holidays."
"On the day of witches I have come to see in admissions up to seven drunk children at the same time," Pelikan adds.
Drinks who spend the night in detoxification under the supervision of doctors, paradoxically, have the advantage that the next day they do not suffer a terrible hangover at home.
The morning headache, caused by dehydration and lack of glucose, is avoided by the injection of a serum with glucose and the nutrients that are missing from the body.
"These carry it much better, for after the agitated night, they rise up well and do not hurt anything."
"They are only confused about where they are," says Pelikan, adding that, often, patients lose their good mood at least when they see the costs they have generated.
Ambulance transfer and hospitalization in a room for serious patients cost a dozen thousand kroner.
"I have often used the cost as a means of educating them, when I tell children directly at the visit how much their drunkenness has cost and that they would have to spend the whole summer in a youth job to earn enough to pay for that night," Pelikán added.
The health insurance, in his opinion perhaps as a regressive measure, which often gives people back the costs of treatment, does not do so in the case of children who drink.
Two L-159 aircraft are first found in foreign hands in Spain
Two L-159 aircraft out of a total of five, for which the Czech Ministry of Defence replaced the Casa C-295M aircraft, left on Tuesday for Seville, where the manufacturer of the Casa-EADS aircraft is located.
This is the first time that a device of this kind has been found in the hands of someone other than the Czech army.
For the time being, they were only abroad for practice or demonstration flights.
This is the bisquare version L-159T1, which so far used the Czech army and was still in a state of flight.
The remaining three aircraft are the L-159 single-position.
These are still preserved in Aer Vodochody and the sales intermediary, the company Omnipol, already took care of them last week.
Jan Peješk, of the defence press department, indicates that it is not yet known when the planes will be physically removed from Vodochody.
"The L-159 single-position aircraft, on the other hand, were separated from the fixed-wing aircraft long ago, with no investments or additional contributions from the Ministry."
"The L-159T1 biplaza were exchanged in their current state," he told Právo Pejšek.
He added that the army did not run out of two-square aircraft, as in May 2009 the army signed with Aer Vodochody a contract of 200 million kroner for the construction of four unnecessary L-159 devices for two-places.
One of the new planes was already received by the army in July, the other will be delivered by the end of the year.
According to Pejšek, EADS committed to the aircraft being added to the equipment of some allied countries.
"The contract clearly states that the company EADS is the one that withdraws the L-159 aircraft and that they will serve for the practices of pilots from NATO countries."
"It is therefore up to the buyer to decide how they will be used in this framework," says Pejšek.
The newspaper Hospodářské noviny published earlier that, for example, the Spanish army is not interested in the L-159.
The exchange of five L-159 for a Casa aircraft and the purchase of three other aircraft for 3.5 billion kroner were approved last year by the Mirek Topolánek government.
The Ministry of Defence did not call for an invitation to tender for the purchase and negotiated directly with EADS.
The current defence management states that the exchange promotes the future export of L-159 abroad.
The Czech army acquired from Aer 72 aircraft and only uses 24, so it wants to sell the rest.
The purchase of Casa aircraft may have judicial consequences.
The European Commission has already denounced the Czech Ministry of Defence to the European Court of Justice because it should choose the aircraft by making a European invitation to tender and not by contacting a single manufacturer.
The army already received three Casa aircraft and the last one should arrive at the Praguense airport of Kbely in 14 days.
An index finger longer than the ring indicates a lower risk of cancer
Men who have the longest index than the annul are subject to a lower risk of prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published Wednesday in a British cancer magazine.
It may depend on the level of testosterone, the male hormone.
"Our results indicate that the relative length of the finger can be a simple test of the risk of prostate cancer, particularly for men up to 60 years of age," said the co-author of the Ros Eeles study, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
Therefore, the finger may help to determine which men should undergo a prostate cancer test, particularly if this feature is associated with a genetic risk or other harmful factors, such as family health problems, as Eeles says.
During the period 1994-2009, he followed up with a British counterpart of more than 1,500 prostate cancer patients and, simultaneously, 3,000 healthy men.
More than half of the participants in the study had the right-hand Indian finger shorter than the ring.
They had the same chance of suffering prostate cancer as 19% of those whose fingers were of the same length.
For men with a longer index than the ring finger, this risk was reduced by 33%; for men below 60% the reduction reached 87%.
The relationship between the length of the two fingers in question, determined in the prenatal period, reflects different levels of hormones to which the fetus is exposed in the matrix.
A lower testosterone level corresponds to a longer index.
Previous studies indicated that testosterone influences the development of prostate cancer.
The great Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, Professor Václav Pačes, told ČTK that he knows the study, but that he does not think that the relationship between the length of the fingers and the cancer can be "fully demonstrated."
