Support for democracy in Latin America, as well as support for private companies, continues to increase.
Crime is of greater concern than unemployment.
In addition, in much of the region, Brazil is seen as a more influential country than the United States.
These are some of the findings of the latest Latinobarometer survey conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively by The Economist.
Since the survey has been conducted regularly since 1995, it allows for a follow-up of changes in attitude in the region.
The results of this year's survey, conducted in September and early October, highlight two related issues.
The first is the relatively lively mood in Latin America.
The second is the growing stability of attitudes towards democracy and its main institutions.
Support for democracy has increased considerably in various countries on the Pacific coast of South America (see table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has reached an average of 6 per cent per year since 2002, support for democracy has increased from a small 40 per cent in 2005 to 61 per cent this year.
It also grew in Mexico, where the economy has recovered after a large decline in production last year.
However, only half of the respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous countries in the area, are convinced Democrats, which reduces the regional average (see figure 2).
Some 44 per cent of respondents in the region expressed satisfaction with the way democracy works in practice in their country, the same figure as last year, but considerably more than 25 per cent in 2001 (figure 3).
About 34 per cent stated that they trusted their country & apos; s Congress and 45 per cent in their Government, the same amount as last year in both cases, but significantly higher than in 2003 (17 per cent and 24 per cent, respectively).
A decade ago, economic turbulence in Latin America seriously affected support for democracy.
The fact that it was maintained during the global financial crisis is likely to be due to the fact that many Latin American countries were only affected by a short recession and enjoyed a strong recovery.
In addition, the existence of a stronger social safety net has helped to protect the poorest.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty only increased marginally in 2009 and that it has been reduced again this year, to 32%.)
However, the mood varies considerably from country to country (see figure 4).
The good economic performance of Brazil and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, is reflected in a general sense of progress.
This feeling is less common in Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more serious and violent crimes have increased.
For the second time since the surveys began, more respondents in Latin America mention crime, rather than unemployment, as the most serious problem your country faces (see figure 5).
About 31 per cent say that, either they or a close relative, he has been a victim of crime in the last year, a figure that has been reduced since 38 per cent last year and is the lowest percentage since 1995.
The most positive economic returns are reflected in increased support for private companies and the market economy: about 71 per cent of respondents in the region claim that private companies are indispensable for development, while in 2007 it was only 56 per cent (see figure 6).
About 58 per cent agree that the market economy is the only system that will allow their country to develop, compared with 47 per cent last year.
It is interesting that 62% of those surveyed in Venezuela are of the same opinion (and 80% support private companies), although their left-wing president, Hugo Chávez, is expropriating many private companies.
Brazil is the country with the highest leadership in the region, as indicated by 19 per cent of respondents (compared to 18 per cent last year), followed by the United States (9 per cent, same figure as last year) and Venezuela (9 per cent compared to 11 per cent a year ago).
However, the United States is the country considered most influential by those surveyed in Mexico and much of Central America, while Venezuela has such a title in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
