However, they were much worse off than the fears of foreigners who were trying to help the country to remount after its problems.
Votes were introduced in the ballot boxes, some people voted several times, ballots thrown in the sewers, polling stations destroyed and acts of intimidation.
The polling stations opened with hours of delay.
Many Haitians, including groups displaced by the January earthquake, wandered around the area trying to find out where they had to vote.
Some of them, in the end, gave up.
A dozen presidential candidates, including several of the most popular, denounced fraud and called for the annulment of the elections.
The protests, some of them violent, spread throughout the country.
However, Edmond Mulet, the largest United Nations official in Haiti, stated that they were "relatively good elections in many ways."
The observers for the Organization of American States and the Caribbean Community said with caution that "we do not believe that these irregularities, however serious, necessarily invalidate the process."
In other words, the show continues.
The electoral authority, which according to its opponents is committed to René Préval, the unpopular outgoing president, and to his candidate, Jude Célestin, should announce the preliminary results on December 7.
The event is expected to take place in January.
Not all hope for the elections has yet been lost.
The two main opposition candidates, Michel Martelly, a rapper, and Mirlande Manigat, a former first lady, have withdrawn their initial request for the vote to be invalidated.
But problems can still arise if the electoral authority states that Mr Célestin, who has little support, if he has any, has moved on to the second round.
In view of the fact that the cholera epidemic rashes the country and more than a million earthquake survivors continue to live in tents, a large abstention is expected.
At the time, many Haitians wanted to vote, but they were not able to do so because of a lack of organization.
Some 250,000 identity documents, necessary to vote, had not yet been distributed shortly before the elections.
There's a lot at stake.
Aid donors regard the election of a popular and legitimate government as an essential step in the reconstruction of Haiti.
And as it has become clear, so do the Haitians themselves.
Moving from the tips to the center
In the weeks that have passed since she lost her husband, Cristina Fernández, the president of Argentina, has enjoyed a great sympathy among the public that has increased her popularity rate by 20 points, to more than 50%, the highest level she has recorded since her election in 2007.
However, that I can turn it into a successful campaign for a second term in next year's elections will depend on whether the clearly affected Mrs Fernández leaves aside the intransigence of her late husband, her predecessor and political partner, Néstor Kirchner.
And at this point, the indications are not conclusive.
Mr Kirchner, who continued to take over economic policy even after his wife succeeded him as president, had the habit of drawing up budgets that undervalued tax revenues, economic growth and inflation.
This allowed the presidential marriage to spend the additional income at its discretion.
In theory, Mrs. Fernández's government lost its majority in Congress last year.
However, the opposition is divided, a situation that has worsened following Kirchner's death as a result of a heart attack on 27 October.
Some dissenting members of the peronist movement in power have faced Mrs Fernández.
However, after some chaotic sessions in which one Member punched another in the face and other Members accused the government of bribery, Congress decided to reject the 2011 budget.
"I'm not going to argue," the president said.
The 2010 budget will therefore be implemented next year, which will give the President an even greater margin of action when spending it.
The economy is improving considerably: it is likely to grow to 9% this year.
The official inflation rate is currently 11.1 per cent, but many private calculations, in addition to the wage requirements of the trade unions, are close to 30 per cent.
Mr Kirchner, who took power in 2003 when Argentina was on the brink of economic collapse, made growth and poverty reduction his priorities, rather than inflation control.
He refused to negotiate with the IMF, put pressure on the private sector and had INDEC, the statistical institute, adapt official inflation statistics.
Will President Fernández now modernise these policies?
It has convened meetings between the private sector and trade union leaders.
In addition, its officials claim that they want to limit wage increases next year to 18 per cent.
The economy has been driven by the high prices of Argentine agricultural exports in the world.
However, inflation has limited the momentum to growth achieved with a large devaluation in 2002.
Perhaps for this reason Mrs Fernández is giving signs of wanting to restore Argentina's financial ties to the rest of the world.
At the beginning of the year, the government reached an agreement with the bond holders who had refused a prior forced debt restructuring that Argentina had not paid in 2001.
At present, it seems that Mrs Fernández is about to conclude an agreement with the creditor governments grouped in the Paris Club, to which she owes about $6.7 billion.
The Kirchner always insisted that this would not involve IMF supervision, as is often the case.
However, last month Amado Boudou, the Minister of the Economy, announced that the Fund will offer "technical assistance" to develop a new national consumer price index, which seems to be the prelude to the cleaning of INDEC.
It is not clear whether President Fernández wants to remain in politics when her term of office ends, given that she no longer has her husband at her side.
If you do, you will need to gain the support of the middle class, much of which has become tired of kirchnerism.
When the Argentines return from their summer holidays in March, the wave of sympathy for it will have fallen.
If you want to win other elections, you will have to decide whether or not you will, calmly, repudiate many of your husband's policies.
Half a hooray for China
Taiwan voters are slowly approaching a kind of closer union with the continent.
What does Taiwan think about his big brother across the strait?
More than 7.5 million voters, 70 per cent of those eligible, went on November 27 to elect mayors and councillors from five urban districts in what seems to be a broad assessment of the president, Ma Ying-jeou.
Mr Ma himself has become an advocate of feelings for the continent, forging innovative business links, including a partial free trade pact, the greatest change in relations with China since 1949.
Mr. Ma passed the test, but for a little while.
Although his Kuomintang (KMT) party ended up winning three of the five municipal elections, he failed to obtain the majority of the votes.
Instead, the Democratic Progressive Party (PDP), which has leaned for total independence from Taiwan, obtained almost 50% of all votes compared to 45% of KMT.
If it had been the presidential, Mr. Ma would be in trouble.
Since his election two years ago, the proportion of his party's votes has decreased by about 8%.
For the first time, the PDP tied with the KMT in the municipalities.
The elections saw the typical elements of the Taiwanese elections, including noisy campaign trucks and large agglomerations with banners and light girls of dancing clothes.
The mysterious attempt to murder rigor was also not lacking.
Sean Lien, the son of Lien Chan, the honorary president of the KMT, was campaigning for one of the KMT candidates the night before the elections.
A man in the crowd shot the young man directly in the face, injuring him and killing a bystander.
The funny thing is that it has not been possible to determine whether the man intended to hurt Lien or take revenge on the candidate.
In any case, says Tsai Ing-wen, the PDP leader, the shooting affected the elections, spreading suspicion about the PDP and causing voters to lean for the KMT.
Maybe the only big winner of the campaign was China.
It was surprising that the issue of the continent itself was not addressed.
Instead, the candidates spoke about public accommodation plans and job creation.
Taiwan usually enjoys its de facto independence and hates China's military threat.
The KMT therefore often avoids publicizing its links with the government in Beijing.
But this time the PDP also avoided encouraging the feeling against China.
It responds to the new awareness that Chinese trade is essential to Taiwan's economic survival.
For his part, Mr Ma stated that it had been confirmed that his policy towards China was acceptable to most Taiwanese.
The Beijing Government is expected to continue to bribe them with trade, in line with its strategy to bring Taiwan back to the fold.
China did not waste time sending a negotiator to Taipei to prepare a summit on investment protection and medical cooperation.
He would certainly also like to achieve political integration, but the first is the first.
The best thing to do is to wait for the 2012 presidential election to happen.
In any case, the PDP has been reinvented.
Two years ago he was in a bad situation: his former leader, Chen Shui-bian, was imprisoned on charges of corruption.
President between 2000 and 2008, he openly instigated explicit independence.
However, under the leadership of Mrs Tsai, a new generation of moderates has emerged and the PDP is working to attract professionals and young people.
Mrs Tsai has been welcomed as a candidate for the PDP for the presidency, as has Su Tseng-chang, who served under Chen.
Now your party is doing its best to show that it can also have relations with Beijing.
Mrs Tsai announced plans to set up a group of experts to act as a point of contact between the PDP and China, provided that negotiations can be carried out without preconditions.
Mrs Tsai tells the Taiwanese public that her party represents a "reliable alternative" to Mr Ma's hasty approach to China.
Mr. Chen seems furious about the change.
In a statement issued from his cell, he stated that the PDP candidates would have been better off if they had insisted that Taiwan was an independent country.
He even ordered Mr. Su, a pragmatic, not to present the presidential.
Even without Mr. Chen being interceed, the PDP will have difficulty in choosing from among its potential candidates.
The KMT should also do an awareness test.
Mr Ma's assessments have been poor, despite the impressive economic growth; the KMT candidates did not want to campaign with him.
Their lack of popularity seems to be mainly due to unemployment and growing differences between rich and poor.
A KMT spokesman claims that he will restructure his cabinet, as well as the local teams.
The large PDP samples suggest that Taiwan's support for an approach is limited.
At the same time, most Taiwanese believe that economic integration with China is inevitable.
According to Antonio Chiang, a well-known columnist, "the point of no return has already crossed."
