Grammy Awards Nominations: Michael Daugherty and Steve Mackey in the best direction of classic albums
Nominations in the field of classical music for the 53rd edition of the Grammy Awards include a mix of musicians and composers from all over the world.
The main nominations were for Michael Daugherty for "Deus Ex Machina," by piano and orchestra, of five movements, and Steve Mackey with "Dreamhouse," a work for eclectic orchestra of three movements.
Among the nominees with links to southern California are the Estonian composer Arvo Pärt for his symphony No. 4, "Los Angeles," a piece commissioned by the Los Angeles Philharmonic and premiered at the Walt Disney Concert Hall in 2009.
The composer based in Los Angeles Avner Dorman is also nominated for his Mandolin Concerto.
Classical music nominations are distributed in 13 categories, including orchestra, opera, coral and solo albums.
The classic producer category of the year includes five nominees: Blanton Alspaugh, David Frost, Tim Handley, Marina and Victor Ledin, and James Mallinson.
The nominees for the classical music album are Bruckner for the Symphonies No 3 and No 4 of the Royal Concertgebouw Orchestra; Daugherty for "Deus Ex Machina" and "Metropolis Symphony" of the Nashville Symphony Orchestra; Steven Mackey for "Dreamhouse" of the Boston Modern Orchestra Project and Synergy Vocals; "Sacrificium - the Art of the Castrati" of several artists; and the "Requiem" of Verdi of the Chicago Symphony and Orchestra. "
In the opera category, the nominees are Berg for "Lulu" of the Royal Opera House orchestra; Adolf Hasse for "Marc Antonio e Cleopatra" of Ars Lyrica Houston; Kaija Saariaho for "L'Amour de Loin" of the Deutsches Symphonie-Orchester Berlin; Rodion Shchedrin for "The Enchanted Wanderer" of the orchestra and choir of the Mariinsky Theatre; and Arthur Sullivan for "Ivanhoe" of the BBC National Orchestra of Wales.
The composers nominated for a Grammy for contemporary compositions include Pärt for Symphony No. 4, Daugherty for "Deus Ex Machina," Hans Werner Henze for "Appassionately Plus," Magnus Lindberg for "Graffiti" and Shchedrin for "The Enchanted Wanderer."
Pärt's # 4 Symphony premiered at the Disney Hall in January 2009 in a session recorded by the Los Angeles Philharmonic, directed by La-Pekka Salonen.
The piece, about 30 minutes, is nicknamed "Los Angeles" and is dedicated to the former oil magnate Mikhail Khodorkovsky, imprisoned in Russia.
The "Mandolin Concerto" by Dorman is nominated for the instrumental soloist performance with orchestra.
The composer of Los Angeles wrote the 15-minute piece specifically to be played in mandolin Avi Avital, who performed the concert with the New York-based Ensemble Metropolis.
"He composed it with sounds from the Middle East and numerous scales and rhythms from North Africa," Dorman said in a phone interview.
Director Pierre Boulez, 85, was nominated in the category of orchestra function, for leading the Chicago Symphony Orchestra during a recording of Stravinsky's works.
The nominated instrumental soloists include pianists Nelson Freire and Marc-André Hamelin; organist Paul Jacobs; violinist Julia Fischer; and archer Sarah Schuster Ericsson.
The nominees as vocal soloists are all women this year: Anne Sofie Von Otter, Cecilia Bartoli, Lucia Duchonová, Vivica Genaux and Measha Brueggergosman.
In the classic mixing category, the soprano Jessye Norman was nominated for her recording of "Roots - My Life, My Song."
