An arsenic-resistant microbium poses the possibility of new life forms on Earth... or elsewhere.
The discovery of a strange bacteria that can use arsenic as one of its nutrients increases the possibility of finding new life forms on Earth and, possibly, on other planets.
Although the researchers discovered the curious bacteria here on Earth, they say it shows that there may be life forms without the main elements they considered essential.
"This body has a double capacity."
"It can grow either with phosphorus or arsenic."
"That makes it a very peculiar thing, although it is not enough to be a really 'alien' type of way of life," said Paul C. W. Davies of Arizona State University, co-author of the report that appears in the Thursday online edition of the Science publication.
For a long time, there are six major essential elements for life: carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulphur.
However, researchers have discovered that the bacteria, found in Mono Lake, California, can continue to grow after replacing phosphorus with arsenic.
"It makes you think about what else is possible," said Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University, co-author of the report.
As Anbar said, finding is important for the search for life on planets other than Earth, as researchers need to be able to recognize life, know what it looks like.
The study focuses on a microbium discovered on Earth.
However, the convening of a press conference to discuss it, in which details of the discovery were not disclosed, generated a great deal of speculation on the Internet about the possibility that the report would indicate the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
He didn't.
What the discovery "does show is that in other planetary environments, there may be organisms that use other elements to boost their biochemistry and that the set of" standard "elements that we consider indispensable for life may not be so fixed," said Charles Cockell, Professor of the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute, Open University, Milton Keynes, United Kingdom.
Cockell was not part of the investigation team.
"This work is novel because it shows the replacement of one element by another in biochemistry and the basic biochemical structure," added Cockell.
The discovery was not by chance made.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of the NASA Institute of Astrobiology, who led the study, focused on the Lake Monkey because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are similar from a chemical point of view, so he speculated that a microbium exposed to both could replace each other.
"Arsenic is toxic mainly because its chemical behavior is similar to that of phosphorus."
"As a result, it may be difficult for organisms to differentiate them."
"However, arsenic is different enough to not work as well as phosphorus, so it goes in and, to put it some way, appeals to biochemical machinery," Anbar explains.
The researchers collected the bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and exposed them to increasing concentrations of arsenic, to which they managed to adapt and used to grow.
The microbium grows better with phosphorus, but the fact that it can live with arsenic in its place raises the possibility that a life form that uses arsenic can naturally exist, whether in other areas of the Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is most common.
Jamie S. Foster, assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, indicated that the idea that arsenic could be replaced by phosphorus was not new, but an example had never been found to prove that it worked.
The arsenic was more common in the first ages of the Earth, he said, so the researchers speculated that the first forms of life may have used it.
"It does suggest that there might be other means of generating life, not just the way life was formed on Earth earlier," said Foster, who was not part of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Health Institutes.
Stolen dogs missing in Compton have been found
The two missing dogs of the four stolen in front of the Bellflower motel have been found, according to Los Angeles County Sheriff's officers on Thursday.
The four competition dogs, two Akitas and two Welsh Corgi Pembroke, disappeared on Tuesday when someone stole the 2006 Chevrolet Express truck in which they were spending the night, in front of the Bellflower Motel 6, authorities said.
Two of the canines recovered on Wednesday afternoon and the remaining two were found on Wednesday, late evening, according to Steve Whitmore, a spokesman for the Los Angeles County sheriff's department.
"The good news is that dogs are all right," Whitmore said.
"They're in good shape."
"They have returned to their rightful owners."
Whitmore did not want to indicate exactly where the dogs were found, in which neighborhood, or the circumstances of the discovery.
"An investigation is under way."
"We don't mean anything," Whitmore said.
"We're following some leads."
The owners of the dogs, Kristina Rickard and David Peek, could not be found to make any comments on Thursday.
They met with their two Akitas at a county animal shelter in Downey on Wednesday afternoon.
The sheriff's assistants found the van and the two dogs separately in Compton.
According to the authorities, the Akitas (Trace, a 3-year-old dog, and Didi, a 10-month-old bitch) had not been damaged.
But Bunny and Peter, the Corgis that Rickard and Peek intended to show at the local competitions this week on behalf of the Japanese dog owners, were still missing until Wednesday night.
Peek and Rickard, who live in Redding, were in town for the AKC / Eukanuba National Championship in Long Beach this weekend and intended to exhibit Trace.
The other dogs were to be shown in other competitions scheduled for the days before the AKC / Eukanuba championship, as Peek told The Times on Wednesday.
Southern California is one of the stops on the couple's almost two-month tour participating in canine competitions.
On Monday night, Peek and Rickard made the check-in at the motel.
They usually stay in motels and park the van right in front of your room window.
They were carrying three other dogs (a boxer's kid, a Parson Russell terrier and a Brittany, who slept with them in the motel room.
But they left the Akitas and Corgis in the van because they have a very thick fur and would be cooler.
They left the windows slightly open so that the dogs could breathe fresh air.
Peek and Rickard reported the van's robbery on Tuesday at 6: 00 in the morning.
Peek had said that they would offer a reward to anyone who could lead them to the Corgis, equipped with microchips to identify them.
It was not clear on Thursday whether a reward would be given or not.
The lion is ready to roar again, while the restructuring of MGM gets final court approval
After 18 months of confusion and uncertainty, MGM has finally got green light to start over.
On Thursday, a federal bankruptcy judge in New York officially approved the "pre-armed" plan by creditors to clear approximately $5 billion in debt, paving the way for the 86-year-old entertainment company to focus its efforts on the production and premiere of films and television programs.
Thursday's ruling confirms that the plan meets the requirements of the American bankruptcy code, so there are no other legal obstacles to MGM relegating under the founders of Spyglass Entertainment, Gary Barber and Roger Birnbaum, who will become the main executives of what will be a reduced study.
The staff will be reduced from 400 to approximately 320.
In fact, MGM will not leave Chapter 11 until JPMorgan Chase closes a $500 million planned credit instrument to finance the operations and productions of the new MGM.
The investment bank is currently syndicating the credit, which on its own is contributing $75 million, and is expected to be funded by mid-December.
The process of restructuring the study began in May 2009, when the investment bank Moelis and Co. was hired to provide advice on the management needed to manage its finances, while fighting to make interest payments for $300 million a year.
In August, Director Harry Sloan was replaced by Stephen Cooper, a former President of Enron and expert in the recovery of bankrupt companies, known for his work at Krispy Kreme Doughnuts.
Moelis and Cooper's attempts to resolve MGM's financial tribulations and satisfy the more than 140 creditors in the study took much longer than expected.
After several months of discussions, at the end of 2009 the parties agreed to put the company for sale.
However, the auction attracted a few bidders and none of them willing to pay the more than $2 billion that creditors were looking for.
Before spring this year, he returned to the design table as the MGM team started working on a restructuring plan that, after months of debate and internal disagreements, was finally supported by creditors at the end of October.
When MGM officially gets out of bankruptcy in the coming weeks, Moelis and Cooper's companies will receive multi-million-dollar bonuses for their work.
Moelis and Co., which has already received $1.2 million, will receive a payment of $9.5 million.
Cooper's companies, which have been raising $375,000 per month for their company management services, will receive a "success fee" of $4 million.
Barber and Birnbaum plan to resume production in MGM, which released only one film this year, and gathered an annual board of seven or eight films that will be released in 2012.
They also plan to co-finance two films based on "The Hobbit," along with Warner Bros.
The study needs to make a separate loan of between $265 million and $275 million to finance its share of those two films, which will be directed by Peter Jackson.
The investor Carl Icahn, who owns about 18% of MGM's debt, had been trying to fix a merger of the study with Lions Gate Entertainment, in which he is the largest shareholder.
However, the recent talks between the two companies did not result in an agreement.
