A more moderate side of order maintenance in China is promoted
As an urban instructor sergeant, Tang Shenbin marked the way in a city square, severely inspecting the nervous people in his charge, issuing orders in a low voice with military authority.
He wanted the chengguan women's members, the corpulent police of China's urban order, feared and despised by their capricious energetic measures and their inclination to violence, to communicate a certain impression to a handful of spectators.
"Signatures!"
"Attention!"
"Show them," he whispered, "how pretty girls are!"
Four girls who barely spent their teens with white gloves and identical olive green jackets and tight pants to draw attention to.
Four pairs of perfectly aligned black shoes.
Four elegant hats placed perfectly on top of the hair tied with blue and white stripes.
"Personally, I think they have a normal appearance," said Mr Tang, disdainly.
"The models are nice."
More than one government has tried to clear the image of China's urban inspectors.
One city ordered all new recruits to have a degree.
The Guangdong Province changed the grayish green color of the uniforms to a supposedly more attractive blue.
Wuhan, in Central China, replaced the use of force with intimidating looks: in 2009, according to a report, 50 officers surrounded a decicolon snack cart, and watched it with a frowning frown constantly for half an hour, until the street seller picked up his things and left.
Xindu, an urban district of 680,000 in Chengdu, has chosen a radical makeover.
Since 2003, the district has added 13 women to its urban police, specifically chosen for their appearance, proportion and youth.
The idea is to give the clumsy police a softer, more feminine side.
Unfortunately, even Scarlett Johansson would have to fight to increase China's meticulous respect for these city squads.
And for a good reason, the critics would argue.
Unlike the police, these officers are only authorized to enforce city ordinances by imposing fines and other administrative penalties.
But Chinese news media routinely portrays a different reality.
In January 2008, inspectors in Hubei Province beat to death a bystander after using his cell phone to film them while dissolving a protest against a waste dump.
