Prosecutors will not press charges against Senator Ensign
The senator's lawyers announced Wednesday that the Department of Justice's prosecutors have exculpated Senator John Ensign of the criminal charges that arose from his affair with a former campaign assistant and his efforts to secure work through lobby for the wife's husband.
The decision ends with the most serious legal threat facing Ensign, the Nevada Republican who was considered as a possible Republican presidential candidate for 2012, until the scandal about his affair had national headlines last year and damaged his career.
Ensign's office said he was "certainly happy" with the decision, which came after an entire year's investigation.
The senator could still face a disciplinary measure of the Senate ethics committee.
Ensign's lawyers said that the Justice Department had "informed us that Senator Ensign is no longer an object of his investigation and that he has no plan to press charges against him on this issue."
The Department of Justice did not want to comment on the case.
The announcement was a surprise to many ethics lawyers outside the Department of Justice, who said there seemed to be significant evidence to indicate that Ensign could have conspired to violate a federal criminal ban on lobby.
The interviews, e-mail and other documents that were first released in October 2009 in the New York Times indicated that Ensign had helped Douglas Hampton, who was one of his assistants, to obtain lucrative work through lobby, to achieve the silence of Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, about the senator's affair with her.
Mrs. Hampton once worked as the treasurer of an Ensign campaign.
Ensign contacted several political sponsors to find Mr. Hampton's work and advocated on their behalf after they had hired Mr. Hampton to lobby for them, according to documents and interviews.
As Hampton had recently been an assistant to Ensign, he was excluded under the law of lobbying for his former employer or the Senate for a year.
The ethics experts said that the unusual arrangement between Ensign and Hampton, who were close friends before the affair, was in disagreement with the so-called "revolving door lobbing ban," which seeks to restrict former state employees from using their connections to do personal business.
From the evidence that has been made public, "it seemed to be a prima facie case of a conspiracy to substantially violate the status of revolving door," said Stanley Brand, a Washington lawyer who specializes in defending government-investigated clients.
While Department of Justice officials refused to explain the reasoning behind the Ensign decision, Mr. Brand and other ethics lawyers said that the department seemed cautious in accepting political prosecutions after several major setbacks to its public integrity section, including last year's decision to drop the trial against former Senator Ted Stevens, in the midst of procedural misconduct charges.
Federal prosecutors "are clearly cowards," said Melanie Sloan, Executive Director of Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington, a defense group that brought several complaints against Ensign in the case.
"This basically means that high-ranking government officials can now assume that the laws do not apply to them," he added.
Paul Coggins, Ensign's main lawyer, said in an interview that he received a phone call from a D.A. 's attorney on Monday and another call the next day, telling him that the department did not want to press charges against his client.
Ensign's defence team had been cooperating with the prosecutors in an attempt to persuade them that the senator, as his office reiterated in a statement on Wednesday, "acted in accordance with the law."
Coggins refused to explain in detail the legal arguments he gave to the prosecutors.
"I'm not comfortable getting into details about my discussions with the Justice Department, I can only say that we think they made the right decision," he said.
Last month, the Federal Election Commission decided to change an investigation into a separate complaint by the ethics group, which claims that a $96,000 payment from Ensign's parents to the Hampton violated federal electoral law.
The election commission said that it did not have enough evidence to prove that the money was nothing but a gift.
NV Energy is an important Nevada company that had long supported the senator, who got a job through lobby thanks to the help Ensign gave Hampton.
An email sent in December 2008 showed that after the company accepted Hampton as a lobbyist, Ensign's chief of staff, John Lopez, contacted Hampton and told him that he was "beating" the Ministry of the Interior on an issue in dispute.
Ensign also attended a lunch with Hampton and another Nevada client, Allegiant Air, and called the transport secretary to set up a meeting on behalf of the airline after he had hired Hampton to lobby.
When for the first time the news of the affair last year appeared, Ensign asked his constituents for forgiveness and resigned his position as the fourth Republican leader in the Senate.
After keeping a low profile for many months, two weeks ago Ensign told journalists that he planned to run for a third term in the Senate.
When Ensign's spokesman, Jennifer Cooper, announced that Ensign was no longer the subject of a criminal investigation, he said that the senator hoped that the ethics committee would quickly follow the example of the Department of Justice and complete its investigation.
"Senator Ensign has a desire to continue his difficult work on behalf of the people of Nevada," he said.
