For decades, the courts of appeal have recognized that the coverage of successful cases can raise questions about the impartiality of a trial.
In a historic ruling of 1966, the U.S. Supreme Court overturned the conviction of a Cleveland osteopath, Dr. Sam Sheppard, for the murder of his wife, saying in his decision, in the Sheppard v. Maxwell case, that there was "a carnival atmosphere in the process" due to the media.
