Defence lawyers say they will also question the constitutionality of the death penalty and argue that the judge incorrectly removed a jury that had criticized the prosecutors, and that he had incorrectly pressed for a verdict for his strange decision to order the jury to deliberate for a weekend.
The jurors were not kidnapped.
But his arguments about the effect of the intense coverage of the process can attract most of the interest.
They observed in a challenge to the verdict filed last month that the case dominated the news in Connecticut and was discussed during the election campaign by candidates for governor and the U.S. Senate.
They argued that the media continuously threw wood into the fire of emotion over the case.
"The daily agglomeration of media tweets, cameras and reporters outside the court," the lawyers wrote, "it was something never seen here in New Haven and perhaps in the whole state."
Your attention to Tweeter's coverage is controversial.
In some interviews, some journalists said that the complaint about the fact that the immediate news was more important than the reports delivered more slowly was a ludicrous vision that would make the court's policy on coverage control weak in future processes.
But some lawyers said that the courts of appeal were often attracted to the arguments about the adaptation required in the courts due to social and technological changes.
Hayes' lawyers are pushing for that claim.
In his writing, they referred to the 1966 Supreme Court decision, which overturned Dr. Sheppard's conviction due to the coverage of the process, and made it clear that they would demand that new means would require new rules.
"This case," they wrote, "represents the Sheppard v. Maxwell case of the 21st century."
Can the civism set up a bridge to join the divisions?
After a remarkable campaign for invectiva and negativity, this week a little civic has been triggered in Washington.
Is it an omen of genuine future bipartisan cooperation or an illusory moment before a quick return to party combat in the capital?
Tuesday's meeting between President Obama and the leaders of Congress did not lead to any progress on the major issues to be addressed during the outgoing session.
But from what everyone says, it was at least a courteous discussion of the differences between the two sides, as well as a recognition of their shared responsibilities to rule, rather than being another empty episode to win party points.
The public meeting on Wednesday of the president's deficit committee was equally civilized, despite the political differences that remain between the members.
It seems clear that close interaction over a period of months generated mutual respect that transcended the ideological gap that still separates members.
That is just enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has come.
Now both sides are in a probationary period, raging at each other to identify signs of cooperation and commitment, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and the patience of voters for a renewed party war.
The reason why the Tuesday meeting and the subsequent assessments of the meeting by the participants were made with a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too large and very deep-rooted to suggest any rapid climate change that existed over the past two years.
Whether it is tax, expenditure, health care or social assistance, the two sides are at opposite poles.
Anyway, the November election has soften the mood in Washington, at least in the short term.
"There is no doubt that things have changed with regard to the way things are said," said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official now at the Center for Ethics and Public Policy.
"They are inevitable after the elections.
The elections wake up party passions, which are then extinguished.
That's good. "
On some issues, particularly those on the agenda of the outgoing session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush's tax reductions are over at the end of the year, and no one is in favour of this.
Both sides want to find a way to preserve some or all reductions, on a permanent or temporary basis.
Similarly, there is likely to be a commitment to expand unemployment benefits, probably because Republicans cannot make them believe that they are in favour of tax reductions for the rich, denying unemployment benefits for unemployed workers.
After Tuesday's meeting at the White House, there is greater optimism for possible treatment of these issues during the outgoing session, along with the ratification of the new START (Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty) nuclear disarmament pact.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation on the pressing issues of the outgoing session will not necessarily lead to a continuous bipartisan when the new 112th Congress meets in January.
He stated, on the contrary, that it is very likely and even inevitable, that a period of disagreement should begin.
"After the things to be done are done, in the short term psychology will turn the situation back to one of confrontation," he said.
Wehner also expressed scepticism (which is widely shared) about the fact that the civism can lead to true cooperation.
"I see most of what will happen between now and 2012 as an essay for the 2012 main event," he said.
The reasons have much to do with the constitution of the new Republican majority in the House and the Tea Party voters, who contributed decisively to its creation.
As much as Republican leaders are aware of the dangers of overreacting to their position, they know that they must try to keep their promises to cut state expenditures and override the new health law.
These partisan lines are already clearly seen in the initial reactions to the recommendations of the deficit commission, which include the reform of the tax code and the increase in some taxes and retirement age, and the reduction of expenditure.
Co-chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken over one of the most difficult jobs in Washington and, according to their own assessment, have forced the question of the public agenda deficit in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the 18-member commission to publish their plan as an official recommendation, and they've been fighting to get close to that figure.
The greatest resistance is among the officials elected on the panel, suggesting that there are at least few grounds or desire for commitment in tax matters.
Galston predicts two phases in the battles between the White House Republicans and those of Congress.
The first will happen next year in the form of party clashes, when the Republicans challenge Obama over the budget, taxes and medical assistance, followed by a period of more two-party cooperation.
What would bring about change?
The public opinion.
There is considerable evidence that, despite the party of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties working together.
If the confrontation leads to a stalemate, as happened in 1995, then both parties will closely observe the reaction of the people.
Whoever they think is losing will probably change course and seek engagement.
However, this can be an optimistic vision.
Partidism and polarization are now greater than they were in the mid-1990s, and there seems to be a larger ideological gap between Obama and Republicans of the Congress than there was between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans at the time.
At the same time, the activists of both parties see 2010 as the mere prelude to a more transcendental election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civilism shown this week can be welcomed by many Americans.
But this will require much more effort on both sides to find common points on the issues that still divide them.
A filtered American document portrays Moscow as the paradise of corruption
The control of the city is in the hands of a "cleptocracy," and leaves a part of the bribes and protection money that the Kremlin collects directly, as reported in February by the US Embassy in Russia.
It was reported that both the police and the Federal Security Service operate huge blackmail systems, which helps explain the high cost of living in Moscow.
They raise money not only from legitimate businesses, but also from organized criminal groups.
Every stratum of bureaucracy, what Prime Minister Vladimir Putin has called "vertical authority," takes his part as the money goes up on the scale.
The note, which was sent to Washington under the name of Ambassador John Beyrle, was published by WikiLeaks on his website on Wednesday.
The note is based on sources whose names have been censored.
It was written while Yuri Luzhkov was still mayor of Moscow, and blames him for much of the corruption.
President Dmitry Medvedev fired him in October, but there has been little evidence of a clean-up since.
Luzhkov and his wife, Yelena Baturina, who has a major construction company, have consistently denied allegations of corruption over the years, and he has won several libel claims about such allegations.
In September, when he was asked on a Russian television channel about a documentary that suggested that he was corrupt, he said, "It's crazy, a scumbag, a nuisance."
According to the polls, the Russians overwhelmingly believe that their society is corrupt.
But it is unusual to find the details explained in detail, as they were in the embassy report, and it is unheard of that it is the diplomats of a foreign country who do that.
"The direct links of the Moscow city government with crime have led some to call it 'dysfunctional', and to say that the government functions more like a cleptocracy than a government," the note says.
"Criminal elements enjoy a 'krysha' (a term of the criminal world and the mafia that literally means" roof "or protection) that is passed through the police, the Federal Security Service (SFS), the Ministry of Internal Affairs (MVD), and the prosecutor's office, as well as all the sectors of the Moscow City government bureaucracy.
"Analysts identify a three-level structure in the Moscow criminal world."
"Luzhkov is at the top."
"The SFS, the MVD and the militia are on the second level."
"Finally, ordinary criminals and corrupt inspectors are at the lowest level."
"This is an ineffective system in which criminal groups fill a gap in some areas, because the city does not provide some services."
The report states that the SFS collects money from the largest companies, and that the police target small businesses.
One source, the report said, "explained that Moscow's commercial owners understand that it is best to get the protection of the MVD and SFS (instead of organized crime groups) as they not only have more weapons, resources and power than criminal groups, but are also protected by law."
"For this reason, protection against criminal gangs is no longer a priority."
The note notes that while money collection is complete, protection may be irregular; even those who pay are subject to arrest.
Those who don't pay quickly find their business closed for one pretext or another.
Medvedev has spoken several times about the fight against corruption, but has confessed that it has made little progress.
The embassy note reports men taking bags, probably full of cash, inside Kremlin himself.
