"But he's a part of this bureaucracy."
"He does not belong to a political class, because there is no longer a political class in Russia."
Without politics, without opposition, without a separation of powers, he said, corruption is inevitable.
At the national level, Indem estimates that corruption costs Russia more than $300 billion per year.
In a recent survey of global perceptions of corruption carried out by the non-governmental organization Transparency International, the country was ranked at 154 (countries are classified at least at the most corrupt).
The disclosure of the US Embassy note, which did not occur until late in the night Moscow time, will surely cause disgust within the Russian government, and even though Luzhkov can be blamed for Moscow's weaknesses, could be an opportunity for the Kremlin to argue that it is solving the problem.
Interviewed for the CNN by Larry King, Putin suggested that WikiLeaks documents could be lies and reacted furiously to a revelation that U.S. diplomats called him Batman and Medvedev Robin.
"The truth of the matter is that this is related to our interaction, which is an important factor of domestic policies in this country," he said.
"But to be honest with you, we do not suspect that this would have been done with such arrogance, with such pressure and, you know, that it would have been done in such an immoral way."
The veterans of the Khmer Rouge forced to face the past
In a specific room with a slightly illuminated, stained and deranged walls, the director of the Anlong Veng High School reminded the man who had built it, the last leader of the Jemeres Rojos Ta Mok.
"Here everyone loves Ta Mok."
"He was a good leader and he cared about his people," said Sreng Kor Ma, 42.
Known as the "Butcher" for his brutality during the Khmer-Red government, the commander remains popular in this remote former Khmer-Red fortress in the north-west of Cambodia, where he built hospitals, bridges and other infrastructure, and where thousands of former soldiers of the organization still live.
But this year, 12 years after the Khmer Red surrendered to the government, the long-held loyalty is finally being challenged in Anlong Veng.
In April, a local forum for truth and reconciliation allowed victims to publicly face people who had participated in the regime.
In June, the government distributed here a high school textbook that for the first time teaches the history of the Khmer Roojos to the children of their former soldiers.
And in July, a joint United Nations / Cambodia court issued the first sentence of a former member of the Khmer Rojos, sentencing the former head of the well-known torture centre Tuol Sleng, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as Duch, to 35 years in prison.
With each of these events, anxiety has grown among the veterans of the Khmer Rojos of Anlong Veng, complicating the efforts for reconciliation and their attempts to reintegrate into Cambodian society.
"There is resentment and fear among the former Khmer Rojos, but they can't do anything," said Chhang Youk, director of the Cambodian Documentation Centre, an independent organization that investigates the regime.
"For them, life under the Khmer Reds was glorious, but the regime has become a symbol of evil."
"This is generating divisions within families."
During the Khmer Rouge government of Cambodia, between 1975 and 1979, approximately 1.7 million people were executed or killed of hunger, disease or overwork.
When in 1979 the Vietnamese invaded and overthrew the Pol Pot-led government, the regime's remains and its military fled to the Cambodia-Thailand border.
There they launched an insurrection that lasted until the last movement that surrendered in December 1998.
Like Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary led the guerrilla war from their bases in the mountains and forests of Western Cambodia, Ta Mok cultivated followers in Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, after a UN-sponsored peace agreement led to the country's first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of Khmer-Red fighters began deserting to the government, culminating in the renditions of Ieng Sary in 1996, and Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998, and Ta Mok, who had resisted, was captured by government forces in 1999 in the nearby Dangrek Mountains.
He died in a prison in Phnom Penh in 2006 while awaiting the trial.
Without the support of their benefactors, the most ancient Khmer Red fighters fell into the absolute misery that is common in rural Cambodia, and many feel nostalgia for the movement.
Although a few elite Jemeres Rojos officers retained their local administrative posts in exchange for laying down their weapons, the soldiers are still poor and unskilled farmers.
"These people have had little benefit after the surrender," said Sok Leang of the Justice and Reconciliation Centre, which offers public forums throughout Cambodia, including in Anlong Veng.
"They have incorporated the regime's utopian agrarian ideology."
"They were raised without any concept to do business."
Sister Lim, 55, who joined the Khmer Rojos when he was a teenager in 1974, fought in the jungle near Anlong Veng before dedicating himself to life as a poor rice farmer in 1998.
"Life with the Khmer Rojos was fine," he said.
"Ta Mok fed everyone."
"But now life is difficult because we have to self-supply."
The current Khmer Red Court has also caused concerns here.
At the beginning of next year, the court is expected to start prosecuting Nuon Chea, Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, Ieng Thirith, another former minister of the Khmer Rouge.
The court's mandate is to prosecute the main leaders and those most responsible for the crimes, but it has not said whether it will pursue cases in addition to those four.
This was not much to calm the fears in Anlong Veng.
Recent media speculation has focused on 64-year-old Im Chaem, who was a district head in Banteay Meanchey province during the Khmer-Red government in the late 1970s.
In 2007, she told the researchers at the Cambodia Documentation Centre that she had monitored the construction of the Trapeang Thma dam, a project in which thousands of forced workers are thought to have died.
During a recent shady afternoon, Im Chaem returned from working in the fields to his house on wooden pilotes on a dirt road on the outskirts of Anlong Veng.
When the sun threw long shadows on the grass, Im Chaem refused to talk about his past in the Khmer Rooks.
She stated that if the court called her, she would not be present.
"Cambodia is at peace and stable," he said.
"If there are more prosecutions, there will be war."
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who defected from the Khmer Rouge in 1978, has also repeatedly warned that there will be instability if the court pursues more suspects, although experts and historians question it.
"Cambodia must dig a hole and bury the past," he said.
But facing the past is just what Cambodia must do to move forward, said Chhang Youk, from the documentation center.
"Reconciliation, according to Khmer, is to reunite the broken pieces," he said.
"It is our obligation to gather these broken pieces so that we can understand."
The center produced the first government-approved textbook on the Khmer Red, called "A History of Democratic Kampuchea," of 75 pages.
It was distributed in Anlong Veng in June as a supplement to the secondary school history textbook of the Ministry of Education, which contains less than four pages on the Khmer Rojos.
As in most of Cambodia, young people in Anlong Veng know little about the Khmer-Red, despite the city's link to the regime.
19-year-old Valeak, a student at the Anlong Veng High School, said that the new textbook helped students understand an important part of their history.
But his parents reacted with scepticism when he took the book home to study.
"My family rejects many parts of the textbook and the court," he said.
"They are suspicious because they are not sure how many people the court will prosecute."
Such resistance has made the reconciliation process complex and difficult, Sok Leang said.
But public forums, the textbook and the court are beginning to have an impact, he said.
In any case, here the Khmer Reds retain a powerful charm.
In the Dangrek Mountains, a road with too many weeds and covered with discarded plastic bags leads to a rectangle of the black soot covered by a rusty roof of tin.
Pol Pot's body was burned here on a lot of tires after his death in 1998.
Noom Sothea, 31, a cell phone salesman on the edge of the road, said he didn't know much about the man who was cremated there.
"But he has a strong spirit and many local inhabitants go there to pray to him," he said.
It was Nuom Sothea's birthday, and later that day he decided to walk to the place of Pol Pot's last break, where he would leave a bunch of mature bananas in the hope of having good luck.
Belarus agrees to give up its weapons-qualified uranium reserve
In a surprise victory for President Obama's campaign to protect nuclear material worldwide, the Belarus government announced Wednesday that it will renounce its highly enriched uranium reserve, a critical component of nuclear weapons.
The deal was revealed in a joint statement published after Foreign Minister Hillary Rodham Clinton met with Belarusian Foreign Minister Sergei Martynov, outside a security summit.
For years, the U.S. government had been trying to persuade Belarus to give up its highly enriched uranium and it seemed that they had reached a point of no return last spring.
But U.S. officials told Washington Post that a couple of operations were carried out with Belarus in the last two months, to remove 84.82 kg of weapons-qualified uranium from a Belarusian research facility.
This prepared the ground for Wednesday's agreement to remove the rest of the material, approximately 227 kg, according to a staff member, who spoke from anonymity due to the confidentiality of the subject.
The agreement appeared to be one of the most important outcomes of the 47-nation Nuclear Security Summit chaired by Obama in April, which excluded Belarus.
And it was apparently a good achievement to secure the invitation of the former Soviet republic to the next summit in 2012.
"I was really fascinated by the fact that they wanted a place at the 2012 Nuclear Security Summit."
"This shows that this process is working," said Ken Luongo, President of the Society for Global Security, a group that promotes nuclear safety.
Clinton said the agreement is "a very significant and important step" taken by Belarus.
In April 2009 Obama promised in Prague to protect all vulnerable nuclear material worldwide in the next four years.
Since then, the US government has helped six countries to get rid of all their highly enriched uranium.
Belarus would be the seventh.
A dozen countries did so under the administration of George W. Bush.
