Without undermining the ability as a pilot of the finally champion, the German Sebastian Vettel, nor the capacity of the Renault engine that drives his car, in the world of Formula 1 has become a legend the "secret weapon" that the multinational Siemens has put in the hands of Red Bull to make it a winning team.
It is actually a powerful process simulation software that the German put on the market in 2007 for purposes far away from high car competition.
Nominated PLM, this powerful computer instrument has been used to design assembly chains of manufacturing factories around the world, power plants, high-precision instruments.
The aim is to reproduce, faithfully simulate the product or process before building it in a real way, thus avoiding avoidable failures and costs.
PLM has facilitated the development of Canon's photographic cameras, Sukhoi's aircraft or Nissan's most famous utility cars.
Siegfried Russwurm, responsible for the industrial division of Siemens, explains that the use of this computer instrument in its Formula 1 factory has allowed Red Bull to design and implement "in a few hours, almost in real time," the modifications, changes and improvements that are detected during the races and in the tests.
Russwurm explains that the spares in 1992 had an average of 10 technicians on their team who were able to introduce a maximum of three or four improvements to the vehicles during each season.
The Red Bull team is currently working on 180 high-skilled young professionals who, equipped with powerful computer equipment, analyse and project all kinds of changes in the bollids.
Siemens' manager explained that PLM software is able to analyze and improve all elements of Red Bull's bollids with the exception of the engine, which is of Renault's full responsibility.
The materials, fuel, aerodynamics and safety elements are modified.
The changes can be carried from the virtual reality of the simulator to the reality in less than 24 hours, thanks to advanced laser and high-tech autokey production systems.
As the only limitation of this madness of technological improvement, there is the $40 million that each Formula 1 team can spend at most in each season to facilitate competition.
Red Bull has set up the high-tech factory to design and produce its bollids in a location about 50 kilometres from London.
These are two buildings where visits are restricted, especially for journalists.
Everything that happens there is considered "high secret."
The staff for this task amount to 580 people, including their two pilots, champion Vettel and Mark Webber.
The hero of Formula 1 of Red Bull, no doubt, is the recent champion Sebastian Vetell.
Among the immense technological resources that the brand of energy drinks has put at the service of its participation in the circuits, other protagonists are hidden whose competition is invaluable and their notoriety null.
The factory's head of technology, Steve Nevey, claims that five years ago it was possible to say that R & D advances in wagon cars contributed 50% of the victories and the pilots were responsible for the rest.
