The provocation of a yellow card in circumstances like this or the like is not a new practice, but rather common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, of the rules not written, but followed, of this sport.
Part of the debate in the related case is due to the fact that it has been starred by a team of the entity of Real Madrid (which in its anthem presupposes nobility and honor, and that in the past has fined its players for similar acts) and the dramatization orchestrated, apparently, by Mourinho, who adds one more episode to its long history of histrionic and provocative technique.
In any case, the debate is about whether this type of behaviour not expressly prohibited by the regulation contradicts the principles of sport, that is, if these actions commit fraud of law; they are, in fact, actions that are respectful of the sports regulation, but seem to be circumventing its meaning.
The question is to examine the type of damage they cause to the sports spirit.
One of the goods that understands the sports spirit is the physical integrity of the opposing players, an aspect that with these actions was not put at risk, that is, there was no violent game.
Another of these assets that is referred to with fair play is to prevent the team of the violators from taking unfair advantage of the opposite team, which did not happen either.
However, the paradoxical thing about the action of the Real Madrid players is that they did not fit into what we normally characterized as a trap or law fraud, because their violation of the rules was not done in secret to try to avoid the punishment, but precisely their action tried to be the most obvious in order to receive the punishment of the referee.
They were waiting and happy to accept the penalty.
Another question is what kind of advantage the offenders get in the intentional misdemeanours examined.
Here it seems necessary to note that the rival is not placed in a disadvantageous position and no benefit is obtained in the same party, as the result of the action clearly means leaving the team itself with fewer players.
And it's not a useful strategy for the next game either, because the club won't be able to count on those players.
The advantage, obviously, is that players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that can threaten their participation in a future game.
But this is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of indetermination, because the team can be eliminated at the first of change, and with this performance the players perform a penalty match and move to the second cycle of cards, in which the suspension by card accumulation occurs with a less than in the first cycle.
So, if you go through rounds, it's not so clear that it's an advantage.
In the end, these actions do not go against the sports spirit, of which it is part of making strategic decisions that favour making the most of what the rules allow.
In the case in question, the players did not act to evade the application of the penalty (this would be a clear case of law fraud), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without circumventing the punishment or fleeing it.
Although the border between ingenuity and law fraud is diffuse, on this occasion I think it was a clear case of ingenuity.
The controversy, I think, arises from two factors: because they were two self-expulsions and the way in which the directive was transmitted to provoke them.
The damage caused to the principles of sport by these actions is not so much ethical as aesthetic.
