EU changes rules to obtain visa
Persons must go to the Visa Applicant Service Centres prior to their interview in the Consular Section; the cost will be lower and the waiting time.
As of 10 January 2011, the procedure for processing a visa at the United States Embassy and consulates will change.
With the new procedure, most applicants will have to go to the Visa Applicant Service Centres (ASC) prior to their interview with the Consular Section.
The ASC staff shall take the applicant's biometric information, which shall be reviewed by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages for applicants, including:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, no longer required to make a payment to arrange the appointment, another payment to process the visa application and another payment for the courier service to deliver the document.
The applicant shall only make a single payment covering all three services.
The current rate will remain unchanged: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visa cases on request (including visas for temporary workers) and $390 for visas for traders and investors.
Persons wishing to renew their visa will not have to go to an interview with the Consular Officer, but will only go to the nearest ASC where they will present their documents and take their prints.
Because biometric information will be taken in the ASC, applicants who require a second appointment to be interviewed in the Consular Section will remain there less time than in the past.
Also, those who apply for a visa at the Consulates in Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra service fee of $26.
For additional information on the new visa application procedure, please visit the following page: http: / / mexico.usembassy .gov / bulletins / sp101201 _ Visas-FAQs.html
