A global plan to renew lighting
Yesterday, the UN in Cancún proposed a plan to renew domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in a hundred countries to reduce greenhouse gases (GHG) by almost one third of the additional decrease to be made to stabilize the climate of the planet by 2020.
This ambitious plan is part of the set of major concrete projects that the UN expects to adopt in Cancun to compensate for the lack of binding reduction commitments in the industrialized countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, if incandescent light bulbs, which still monopolize between 50 and 70% of the market, were to be replaced by fluocompact light bulbs or, even better, by electroluminescent diode (DEL or "LED") bulbs, much of the 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of GHG emitted on the planet would be avoided to illuminate humans.
Lighting is responsible for 8 per cent of global emissions.
It is the equivalent of 70% of the emissions of the global car park.
In Copenhagen last year, major emitting countries, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed themselves to voluntary reduction plans that should reduce global GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, 5 Gt of this amount should still be reduced to stabilize, by 2020, the increase in temperatures by two degrees Celsius to prevent it from getting out of control.
In incandescent light bulbs, 95% of the energy dissipates in the form of heat and the rest, i.e. 5%, produces light.
In the case of fluocompact bulbs, energy spending is reduced by 75% and with new LED bulbs, energy consumption is still reduced twice as much.
Fluocompact bulbs last an average of 6,000 to 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, such as those launched by the manufacturer Philips this week (a company that has also participated in the UN study), have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent bulb, which allows us to give us an idea of the savings that can be achieved with the replacement plan to be implemented in a hundred countries.
These new bulbs can also work with reostates and emit very little heat.
Above, they do not contain any mercury.
Several specialists have expressed their reservations regarding fluocompact light bulbs, as they contain mercury and should be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless the manufacturers provide instructions.
However, the report indicates that the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the fluocompact light bulbs, but the coal thermal power plants, which emit a large amount of mercury to produce the electricity that is dumped with incandescent light bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury per year.
The report details the benefits that this international programme would offer to each country.
For example, Indonesia would thus save one billion dollars a year in electricity and eight million tons of CO2, that is, the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power plants whose construction would cost it 2.5 billion.
