This is not only because the authors of occult texts do not want to do unpublished research (or do not know where to look for news about the non-existent), but because those who are engaged in occult do not only trust what they already know, which reconfirms what they have already learned.
This is the mechanism of Dan Brown's success.
The same applies to secret files.
The informer is lazy, just as he is lazy (or has little desire) the head of the secret services (if he could not be, what I know, editor of the Libération), who only considers true what he can recognize.
The top secret information about Berlusconi sent by the United States Embassy of Rome to the State Department was the same as the Newsweek published the previous week.
Then why have the revelations of these files caused such a stir?
On the one hand, they only say what every cultivated person already knows, that is, that the embassies, at least since World War II and since the heads of States can call on the phone or take the plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic role and, with the exception of some limited representation exercises, have become espionage centres.
Any spectator who sees research films knows it perfectly, we just seem to know that we don't know it for hypocrisy.
In any case, the fact that it is repeated publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy and gives a bad picture of American diplomacy.
Secondly, the idea that any hacker can consult the most secret secrets of the world's most powerful country significantly affects the prestige of the State Department.
The scandal therefore affects both the victims and the "executioners."
But let us enter into the true nature of what has happened.
Earlier, in the time of Orwell, it could be conceived of as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
Orwell's prophecy has come true since, being able to control every movement thanks to the phone, every transaction made, hotel visited, highway taken, the citizen thus became a complete victim of the eye of power.
But when it is shown, as is now the case, that even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control relationship ceases to be unidirectional and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen (at least the hacker, chosen as the avenger of the citizens) can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that can no longer keep its own secrets be held?
It is true, as Georg Simmel already said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that any knowledge of the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is in fact an empty secret, without secret, since it comes from the public domain; but to discover, as WikiLeaks has done, that Hillary Clinton's secrets were empty secrets means to take away all power.
