At present, it is the embassies who are asking the press for confidential information.
Climate: France's sluts in its financing promises
One year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to examine whether the rapidly unlocked funding pledges (fast start or early) made by developed countries have been respected.
And the French sluts have been revealed.
In the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries committed to providing $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union committed to contribute EUR 7.2 billion over three years and France EUR 1.260 billion (i.e. EUR 420 million per year).
During the opening of COP16, the EU has put its best letters on the table to convince its partners that their commitment to fast start financing is true: a report detailing the actions of its Member States, a press conference, a major complementary event, the distribution of brochures...
The operation of transparency proved to be significant and was appreciated for what was really worth: developing countries and civil society would want all developed countries to do the same and with the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released 2010 €2.2 billion, which puts it on the right path to meeting its commitment of €7.2 billion in 2012.
But if we study the situation in detail, things are more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Agreement, money must be "new and additional" to ensure that a complementary effort is made without prejudice to official development aid.
Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached on what "new and additional" means.
When the European Commission proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, have blocked the procedure.
At present, each person chooses the reference that is best suited to him.
For example, the European Commission has taken the year 2009 as a reference: international funding is maintained and 150 million are added in three years as fast start financing.
Other countries have chosen similar references for the year or level of official development assistance.
On the contrary, France considers that the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 is "new and additional."
In other words, no reference is made to the expenditure of the previous years or to the total level of official development assistance.
In particular, the total amount of France's aid to developing countries may remain stable (or even lower), while it seeks to respect its commitment to "new and additional" funds...
Another crucial element, the distribution between grants and loans.
Once again, there is no rule and each one chooses the method of calculation.
Some, like France, consider that each euro borrowed is equivalent to a donated euro.
This is, of course, difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
Although the use of loans may be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often projects related to the reduction of emissions that are based on more effective technologies), it is wrong to present a euro that is to be recovered as equivalent to a euro that is donated... At most, only the cost of the loan to the country that grants the loan (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate) should be computed for its commitments.
But France does not find such reasoning useful: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by making 91.5% of loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% of donations (36.1 million euros); see the EU document for its own eyes.
This is the only country in the Union that uses the loan so often.
Germany uses it by 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia, among others, respect its commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the majority of the European Union provides a euro to meet its commitment, France only provides ten cents and considers the effort to be comparable.
A good trick!
In short, in its fast start funding, France is making a double abuse: on the one hand, in relation to actions over time and, on the other, in relation to the real financial effort.
By spending only EUR 36.1 million, he gets the impression that he spends 420 million "new and additional" as he had promised.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that it is Bercy who has dealt with arbitration) could have a negative double impact, both within the EU (why would the other Member States continue to donate when they can just lend?) and in the negotiations, as developing countries are not foolish...
The chapter on early financing is a little, relatively short-term, in relation to all the climate negotiations.
But it could be an extra grain of sand in the immense machinery that is the CMNUCC.
Let's hope that's not the case.
Whatever it is, it is essential to learn from this first year of early financing.
First, France could announce a change in its method of calculation for the years 2011 and 2012, with the intention of respecting its commitments and in the same way as the other countries of the European Union.
But, in particular, France could make progress in the discussions on the stakes at stake in relation to long-term financing (another essential chapter currently under discussion): we will not get away with the question of "additional character" or the method of calculating loans.
France could change its position to become as progressive on this issue as it is with others.
We therefore have the hope of the new Minister of the Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about France's fast start and its vision of the "additional character" and the use of loans would help to improve the level of international confidence needed to move the negotiations forward.
