The association, which warns that its results "do not have a significant statistical value in view of the limited number of samples analysed, but are illustrative of the problem treated," acquired in supermarkets in Oise and Paris between July and September the food that is usually consumed by a ten-year-old child in four meals and one snack a day.
These foods taken as a model, which respect official recommendations (five parts of fresh fruit and vegetables, three parts of dairy products and 1.5 litres of water per day), as well as the sweets, were examined in laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The balance of the dish is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, of which 42 are classified as possible or likely carcinogens and five are classified as safe carcinogens, as well as 37 substances that are likely to act as endocrine disruptors (PE), according to studies of various institutions such as the International Research Centre on Cancer.
"Although in almost all cases the legal limits for each of the chemicals are not exceeded individually, our study clearly shows that the exposure of consumers to possibly carcinogenic pollutants and / or PE is worrying," the association points out.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than a dozen possible carcinogenic residues and three considered safe carcinogens, as well as about 20 residues that may harm the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, intended as a snack for school, contains traces of six chemical substances, including a fungicide prohibited in France.
The same applies to the green beans in Kenya, included in food, where the study has detected traces of a powerful insecticide prohibited in the EU.
In addition, Russian filet, tin tuna and even bread bar or gum were seasoned with pesticides and other chemicals.
In the tap water, the analyses found the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
At dinner, the salmon slice was the most "nutritious" with 34 chemical residues detected and even the analysis of the plastic plate used to heat the food in the microwave was not completely clean.
The final risk to the consumer of these "pollutant cocktails" is "probably underestimated," says the study.
The Europe Ecology-Les Verts (EE-LV) Alliance, for its part, has proposed "in view of the gravity of the situation" to apply a moratorium on the use of pesticides to stop "the increase in diseases associated with civilization."
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EASA) indicated the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, of which 76 in cereals.
